04651nam a22006975i 9780271035024DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710350247 a10.1515/97802710350242doi  a(DE-B1597)583727  a(OCoLC)233649839  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPS374.C36bS53 2008eb 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813/.30935532221 aShapiro, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Culture and Commerce of the Early American Novel :bReading the Atlantic World-System /cStephen Shapiro. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Method and Misperception: The Paradigm Problem of the Early American Novel -- t2. The Geoculture of the Anglo-French Eighteenth-Century World-System -- t3. The Re-export Republic and the Rise of the Early American Novel -- t4. The Paradox of the Public Sphere: Franklin's Autobiography and the Institution of Ideology -- t5. Wieland and the Problem of Counterinstitutionality -- t6. Arthur Mervyn and the Racial Revolution of Narrative Consciousness -- tAfterword: Early Nineteenth-Century American Studies and the World-Systems Perspective -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTaking his cue from Philadelphia-born novelist Charles Brockden Brown's Annals of Europe and America, which contends that America is shaped most noticeably by the international struggle between Great Britain and France for control of the world trade market, Stephen Shapiro charts the advent, decline, and reinvigoration of the early American novel. That the American novel "sprang so unexpectedly into published existence during the 1790s" may be a reflection of the beginning of the end of Franco-British supremacy and of the power of a middle class riding the crest of a new world economic system.Shapiro's world-systems approach is a relatively new methodology for literary studies, but it brings two particularly useful features to the table. First, it refines the conceptual frameworks for analyzing cultural and social history, such as the rise in sentimentalism, in relation to a long-wave economic history of global commerce; second, it fosters a new model for a comparative American studies across time. Rather than relying on contiguous time, a world-systems approach might compare the cultural production of one region to another at the same location within the recurring cycle in an economic reconfiguration. Shapiro offers a way of thinking about the causes for the emergence of the American novel that suggests a fresh approach to the paradigms shaping American studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCapitalism in literature. 0aCommerce in literature. 0aConsumption (Economics) in literature. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271035024?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271035024423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271035024/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK